Staggered Animations with Timelines

In the last lesson, you learned how to control the timing of each animation using the Position Parameter. Now, let’s add another of style: staggered animations.

You’re already familiar with stagger - those small delays that make animations flow naturally. Now, let’s see how to integrate stagger with timelines to create really engaging sequences.

Stagger in Timelines: Quick Setup

When you use stagger within a timeline, it acts the same way it does in a single tween - adding those nice delays to each item’s animation. But because you’re in a timeline, everything else stays in perfect sync.

Here’s a minimal example:

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.from("h1", {
yPercent: 200,
opacity: 0,
duration: 1,
ease: "power1.inOut",
}).from(
".box",
{
opacity: 0,
stagger: 0.02,
duration: 2,
ease: "power1.inOut",
},
"<0.5"
);

Result 

import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.from("h1", {
  yPercent: 200,
  opacity: 0,
  duration: 1,
  ease: "power1.inOut",
}).from(
  ".box",
  {
    opacity: 0,
    stagger: 0.02,
    duration: 2,
    ease: "power1.inOut",
  },
  "<0.5" // Start 0.5 seconds before the previous animation ends
);
Animation Details
First Animation

The heading <h1> slides up and fades in smoothly.
We’re using yPercent: 200 to move it downwards off-screen initially.
The ease makes it flow naturally.

Second Animation

All .box elements fade in one by one with a stagger effect.
stagger: 0.02 makes each .box appear with a slight delay after the previous one.

Timing with <0.5

The second animation overlaps the first - starting 0.5 seconds before the first one is done.
This creates a nice, seamless transition.

Stagger within a timeline like this helps you create layered, natural-looking animations. You’re not just animating in a straight line anymore - you’re adding flow and texture.

Try adjusting the stagger to see how it changes the feel of your animation! For example, a bigger stagger like 0.1 will make it more dramatic, while a smaller stagger like 0.02 makes it snappy.

That’s it for stagger in timelines with overlapping animation! Play around with these values and see how they can transform the feel of your sequences.
